# `20 min` Introduce FLUX

- React created a way to share a store within the entire application.
- Flux can be seen as an implementation of MVC on the front end side.
- MVC = Model View Controller
- Instead of Model View Controller here it is called: Model, View, Actions
- The context-api will take care of propagating the store to all the views (re-render)

![Context API](https://ucarecdn.com/051c4b0f-1c52-4cbe-a1b0-1d5fb074b8c4/)

⚠️ Its a great idea to install the [react-hello-webapp boilerplate](https://github.com/4GeeksAcademy/react-hello-webapp) and show/explain the demonstration that comes with it.

Install it with the class.

### The Views

- The views are your components that you don't re-use, like `<AboutUs />` or `<Home />`.
- You other componets are not called views because they are meant to be reused in several projects like: `<Card />`, `<Carousel />` or `<Navbar />`

```jsx
    //example render method accessin the store and actions
    render(){
		return <Context.Consumer>
            {({ actions, store }) => {
				return (
				    <ul>
				    {
				        store.favorites.map(f => 
				            <li onClick={() => actions.someAction(f)}>
				                {f.name}
				            </li>
				        )
				    }
				    </ul>
				)
			}}
		</Context.Consumer>
	}
```

### The Actions

- Actions are triggered by the views onClick, onMouseOver or any other event.
- Actions have only two purposes: 
    - Call API's to update the database.  
    - Update the store for any particular purpose (add, update, delete).
- Examples of actions can be: login, createStudent, removeStudent, etc. Actions names should be descriptive about the business.

```js
	const addToFavorites = elm => {
		const store = getStore();
		setStore({ favorites: store.favorites.concat([elm]) });
	};
```

### The Store

Its a container of information shared on your entire application:

- You have to initilize the store with `null` or `[]` or `''` depending on your the data-type your are storing.
- The biggest challenge on the store is modeling your data: What structures should y use? What is better to store like an array than an object?
- You can access your store from your views in a read-only mode.

```js
